      "id": 342086,
      "is_answer_order_important": false,
      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p>Some p<i>K</i><sub>a</sub> data for simple dibasic acids is shown. How can you account for the fact that the difference between the first and second ionization constants decreases with increasing distance between the carboxyl groups?</p>\n<table class=\"unnumbered\">\n<tbody><tr>\n<th><b>Name</b></th>\n<th><b>Structure</b></th>\n<th><b>p<i>K</i><sub>1</sub></b></th>\n<th><b>p<i>K</i><sub>2</sub></b></th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Oxalic</td>\n<td>HO<sub>2</sub>CCO<sub>2</sub>H</td>\n<td>1.2</td>\n<td>4.2</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Succinic</td>\n<td>HO<sub>2</sub>CCH<sub>2</sub>CH<sub>2</sub>CO<sub>2</sub>H</td>\n<td>4.2</td>\n<td>5.6</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Adipic</td>\n<td>HO<sub>2</sub>C(CH<sub>2</sub>)<sub>4</sub>CO<sub>2</sub>H</td>\n<td>4.4</td>\n<td>5.4</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table>",
